First, let’s include all the necessary libraries we need:

library(dplyr)
library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)

Next, let’s set up the initial dataset:

IncomeData <- read.csv("~/materials/minor/lab09/Income_Data.txt", header = F, col.names = c("income", "sex", "martial_status", "age", "edu", "ocupation", "living_time", "dual_incomes", "pers_in_house", "pers_in_house_under18", "householder_status", "type_of_home", "ethnic_cl", "lang"))

IncomeData <- within(IncomeData, {
  sex <- factor(sex)
  martial_status <- factor(martial_status)
  edu <- factor(edu)
  ocupation <- factor(ocupation)
  living_time <- factor(living_time)
  dual_incomes <- factor(dual_incomes)
  householder_status <- factor(householder_status)
  type_of_home <- factor(type_of_home)
  ethnic_cl <- factor(ethnic_cl)
  lang <- factor(lang)
  age <- ordered(age)
  pers_in_house <- ordered(pers_in_house)
  pers_in_house_under18 <- ordered(pers_in_house_under18)
})

Let’s try to build a tree. I decided to include all available parameters as independent variables as long as after conducting a few experiments I’ve noticed that if we select smaller number of independent variables then the performance of the model decreases.

set.seed(1)
income.tree = rpart(income~., data = IncomeData, control = rpart.control(cp = 0.001), method = "anova")
income.tree.mod = rpart(income~., data = IncomeData, control = rpart.control(cp = 0.02), method = "anova")
min = which.min(income.tree$cptable[,"xerror"])
min.mod = which.min(income.tree.mod$cptable[,"xerror"])

Ok. Fine. It’s time to discover what does cp parameter stand as the value of control parameter of rpart function.

So, I’m going to look at values of errors using printcp command.

We see that the minimum cv error is 0.6207007, which is higher than in the first case (cp = 0.02).

It’d be nice to note that with cp=0.02 the number of used variables is significantly less than with cp=0.001; hence the tree is less complicated as well, because it actually has smaller amount of levels. Furthermore, the number of steps (decreasing the cp) taken is 32 in the first case, and only 5 in the second case. So, in my opinion, the second way of building a tree might be less accurate and I guess the fact that the minimum xerror in the first case is less than in the second case proves that. Also, I read documentation and found out that cp parameter is one of the parameters which control aspects of how the tree is fitted. According to docs, the overall R-squared increases by cp at each step, and the main role of the cp parameter is to save computing time by pruning off splits that are not worthwhile to be in our model. ***

Let’s make a prediction and see how good it is:

income.tree.pred=predict(income.tree, data = IncomeData, type="vector")
RMSE <- sqrt(mean((income.tree.pred-IncomeData$income)^2))
COR <- cor(x=income.tree.pred, y=IncomeData$income, method="spearman")

Now let’s prune our tree where cross-validation error is taking its minimum value and then see if it’s any better than the first model.

ptree <- prune(income.tree, cp=income.tree$cptable[min,"CP"])
prp(ptree)
 
plotcp(ptree)
 
printcp(ptree)

If we compare the RMSE of the first model which is 1.966269 with the second one 1.9725373, it’s obvious that the first value is less than a second value, which leads to a conclusion that the first model (not pruned) is better than the model based on the pruned tree. Although, the difference is not that big, in my opinion. We can also look at the correlation between the predicted values and the values from the initial data set. In the first case correlation equals 0.6939795, which is a little bit bigger than after pruning the tree: 0.6913496. Which, again, leads to a conclusion that the first model performs better.

Ok. So, let’s get back to our tree and try to describe it in some way. Let’s color it so it’s easier for us to see in which cases income is low and where it’s high as hell (it’ll be colored in red).

set.seed(1)
income.tree = rpart(income~., data = IncomeData, control = rpart.control(cp = .001), method = "anova")
heat.tree(income.tree, type=4, varlen=0, faclen=0, fallen.leaves=TRUE)

Let’s take the greenest one (with the lowest income) and the most red (with the highest income) and try to determine who these people are.

If a person rent a household or lives with parents or family, his age is from 14 to 17 and his ocupation is professional/managerial or he’s a student at high school/college or a homemaker then the person’s income is less than $10k.

If a person owns and grad study then his annual income is around $60k.

Now, let’s assume that we have a person, whose householder status is ‘own’, sex is male (1), type of home is apartment (2), martial status is married (1), age is 26 (3), education is college graduate (5), ocupation is proffessional/managerial (1). Then, according to our tree, the annual income of such person is around $46k (7.6).

Also, a few words about the relation between income and other variables: if we look at the root node of our tree than we can see that there’s a householder status, so I guess income depends heavily on it. We can conclude that age, martial status and ocupation play significant role in person’s annual income. However, such parameters as the language spoken most often, time being in the area and the amount of persons in the house under 18 don’t have impact on person’s income.

income.tree = rpart(income~., data = IncomeData, control = rpart.control(cp = .02), method = "anova")
heat.tree(income.tree, type=4, varlen=0, faclen=0, fallen.leaves=TRUE)
